2025-12-02  Chris Beck  <beck.ct@gmail.com>

	add optional integration with tracing-log
	tracing-log is a bridge that allows tracing to pick up log messages
	written by older rust libraries that used the `log` crate facade.
	the bridge subscribes to log messages and resubmits them as tracing
	events.

	because of lifetime issues, it can't take the log message file and
	line numbers and register them directly as file and line numbers of
	the tracing events. instead it places them as `log.file` and `log.line`
	in the event metadata. then, when using `tracing-subscriber`, the
	metadata are "normalized" by repopulating the file and line number
	information. This normalization is possible when `tracing-log` feature
	is turned on.

	in this commit we mirror this behavior, so that tracing-rfc-5424 will
	also make log messages carry this metadata just as well as tracing messages,
	if the optional `tracing-log` feature is turned on

2025-12-02  Chris Beck  <beck.ct@gmail.com>

	allow sending tracing metadata (target, file/line, module_path) as syslog structured data
	this adds optional features to pass on more of the metadata from the tracing infrastructure
	as structured-data, when using RFC-5424 format.

	it doesn't go as far as sending fields and valuesets from tracing events, but still seems
	like a significant improvement.

	note that `tracing_subscriber` typically defaults to formatting the target
	with the log message in text logs, so many users are used to seeing that in text logs,
	but it's not present in the syslog records produced by this crate before this change.
	in tracing_subscriber, the file and line number are optional defaulting to off.
	in this PR we make all this stuff default to off, for backwards compatible behavior.

2025-11-28  Michael Herstine  <sp1ff@pobox.com>

	Cut release 0.1.5

2025-11-25  Michael Herstine  <sp1ff@pobox.com>

	Fix issue #14.
	Switch from `to_rfc3339()` to `to_rfc3339_opts()` with an argument
	of `SecondsFormat::Micros`. This will format all timestamps (for
	the `Rfc5424` formatter with exactly six digits in the subsecond
	field, compliant with RFC 5424. The prior implementation produced
	variable-sized fields, up to nine digits (I believe).

	Add a regression test for the bug.

